# Command yazi

## What does this command do:

fast terminal multi-media file manager

## Installed from

For Fedora install using: `sudo dnf install yazi`
For Raspberry Pi install using:
```
sudo apt update
sudo apt install ffmpeg 7zip jq poppler-utils fd-find ripgrep fzf zoxide imagemagick file
sudo apt update
sudo apt install build-essential curl file pkg-config libssl-dev

curl https://sh.rustup.rs -sSf | sh
. "$HOME/.cargo/env"

cargo install --locked yazi-fm yazi-cli
cargo install --force yazi-build
mkdir -p ~/.local/bin
cp -f ~/.cargo/bin/yazi ~/.local/bin/yazi
cp -f ~/.cargo/bin/ya ~/.local/bin/ya
```
For Mac install using: `homebrew install yazi`

## Command path

For Fedora run: `yazi`
For Raspberry Pi run: `yazi`
For Mac run: `yazi`

## Command documentation

Docs can be found at https://yazi-rs.github.io/

## Command options

# Launch yazi at a specific path:
yazi [path]

# Write the current working directory to a file on exit (useful for shell integration):
yazi --cwd-file <file>

# Write selected files to a file when open is fired:
yazi --chooser-file <file>

# Clear the cache directory:
yazi --clear-cache

# Use a specific client ID (must be globally unique):
yazi --client-id <id>

# Report local events to stdout:
yazi --local-events <events>

# Report remote events to stdout:
yazi --remote-events <events>

# Print debug information:
yazi --debug

# Print version:
yazi --version

# Print help:
yazi --help
